const a="Duryodhana",e=[{title:"Birth and Early Life",content:"Duryodhana was born as the eldest son of King Dhritarashtra and Queen Gandhari. His birth was marked by ill omens, yet he grew up as the crown prince of Hastinapura, trained in warfare, governance, and martial skills."},{title:"Education and Training",content:"He was trained under Guru Drona and Kripacharya, excelling particularly in mace combat. His closest companion was Karna, to whom he remained loyal throughout his life."},{title:"Jealousy of the Pandavas",content:"Duryodhana’s envy of his cousins, the Pandavas, especially Yudhishthira and Bhima, grew as they excelled in skills, gained popularity, and received affection from the elders. This jealousy became the root of his lifelong rivalry."},{title:"Palace of Illusions and Rivalries",content:"Humiliated by the grandeur of the Pandavas’ Palace of Illusions (Maya Sabha), Duryodhana’s jealousy deepened, further fueling his desire to defeat them at any cost."},{title:"The Game of Dice",content:"Guided by his uncle Shakuni, Duryodhana conspired to defeat Yudhishthira in a game of dice. This resulted in the Pandavas losing their kingdom, wealth, and Draupadi, leading to their exile."},{title:"Role in the Kurukshetra War",content:"As the leader of the Kauravas, Duryodhana played a central role in the Kurukshetra war. He was a courageous warrior and inspired loyalty among his allies, but his arrogance blinded him to the consequences of war."},{title:"Friendship with Karna",content:"One of Duryodhana’s noblest traits was his unwavering friendship with Karna. Despite Karna’s low birth, Duryodhana crowned him King of Anga, standing by him against all odds."},{title:"Defeat and Death",content:"In the final battle, Duryodhana fought Bhima in a mace duel. Despite his skill, he was defeated through Bhima’s strike to his thigh, a violation of combat rules but fulfillment of Bhima’s vow."},{title:"Legacy",content:"Duryodhana is remembered as both a villain and a tragic hero. While his pride and envy led to destruction, his bravery, loyalty, and leadership make him one of the most complex characters of the Mahabharata."}],t={name:a,fullBiography:e};export{t as default,e as fullBiography,a as name};
